'''Houssem-Eddine Chaâbane Aouar''' ({{Langx|ar|حُسَام الدِّين شَعْبَان عَوَار}}; born 30 June 1998) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Saudi Pro League]] club [[Al-Ittihad Club (Jeddah)|Al-Ittihad]]. Born in France, he plays for the [[Algeria national football team|Algeria national team]].

Graduating from the youth setup of Lyon, Aouar spent his professional career at the club for seven seasons before he joined the Italian club Roma in 2023. After playing one season with the Italian club, he joined the Saudi Arabian club Al-Ittihad in 2024.

Aouar is a former youth international for France. He made one appearance for the country at senior level before [[List of association footballers who have been capped for two senior national teams|switching]] his allegiance to Algeria in 2023. He represented the latter country at the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].

==Early life==
Houssem-Eddine Chaâbane Aouar<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/j/j28076.html |title=Aouar: Career history |website=BDFutbol |access-date=11 November 2025}}</ref> was born on 30 June 1998 in [[Lyon]], Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/FootballFicheJoueur58614.html |title=Houssem Aouar |newspaper=L'Équipe |location=Paris |access-date=3 July 2022 |language=fr}}</ref> to parents from [[Béni Saf]] in Algeria.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://dzballon.com/2020/03/05/la-famille-daouar-de-beni-saf-lincite-a-choisir-lalgerie |title=La Famille d'Aouar de Beni Saf l'incite à Choisir l'Algérie |language=ar |work=dzballon.com |publisher=Rabah Farid Kada |date=5 March 2020 }}</ref> He grew up in [[Villeurbanne|Villeurbane]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Merci Houssem Aouar |url=https://www.ol.fr/fr/actualites/merci-houssem-aouar |access-date=2024-01-08 |website=www.ol.fr}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Lyon===
[[File:20191002 Fußball, Männer, UEFA Champions League, RB Leipzig - Olympique Lyonnais by Stepro StP 0139 (cropped).jpg|left|170px|thumb|Aouar playing for Lyon against [[RB Leipzig]] in a Champions League match in 2019]]

Aouar joined the [[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|Olympique Lyonnais Academy]] in 2009 at the age of 11.{{citation needed|date=December 2020}}

He signed a three-year professional contract at [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] in July 2016. He made his first team debut in on 16 February 2017 in a 4–1 away win over [[AZ Alkmaar]] in the first-leg match of the round of 32 of the knockout phase of the [[2016–17 UEFA Europa League knockout phase|UEFA Europa League]], replacing [[Sergi Darder]] after 84 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/02/16/europe/uefa-cup/stichting-az/olympique-lyonnais/2380729/|title=AZ Alkmaar vs. Lyon - 19 February 2017 - Soccerway|publisher=soccerway.com|access-date=19 February 2017}}</ref> Aouar scored his first goal for Lyon's first team a week later in the second-leg match against AZ Alkmaar
at [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]], which Lyon won 7–1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/02/23/europe/uefa-cup/olympique-lyonnais/stichting-az/2380730/|title=Lyon vs. AZ Alkmaar - 23 February 2017 - Soccerway|publisher=soccerway.com|access-date=24 February 2017}}</ref> He made his [[Ligue 1]] debut by starting in the away match against [[SC Bastia|Bastia]] on 16 April 2017, but the match was abandoned at half-time with the score at 0–0. A win was given to Lyon three weeks later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olweb.fr/fr/article/ligue-1-l-ol-se-voit-attribue-la-victoire-a-bastia-30857.html|title=Ligue 1 : L'OL se voit attribuer la victoire face au Sporting Club de Bastia|publisher=olweb.fr|access-date=11 May 2017}}</ref> He was nominated for the Golden Boy award in July 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/golden-boy-2018-award-nominees-12831532|title=Golden Boy 2018 award nominees announced|first=Jake|last=Polden|date=2 July 2018|website=mirror}}</ref>

At the beginning of the 2017–18 season, despite having played only five competitive matches for Lyon's first team since he joined the club, Aouar was given the symbolic number 8 (having previously been worn by club legend [[Juninho Pernambucano|Juninho]]) left free when [[Corentin Tolisso]] left the club for [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=OL: les numéros de Tolisso et Lacazette réattribués |url=https://rmcsport.bfmtv.com/football/ol-les-numeros-de-tolisso-et-lacazette-reattribues-1212921.html |website=RMC Sport |access-date=14 June 2020 |language=fr |date=9 July 2017}}</ref>

On 11 December 2019, Aouar scored a goal against [[RB Leipzig]] in a [[2019–20 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] group stage match<ref name="SkySports">{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/lyon-vs-rb-leipzig/420428|title=Lyon 2 - 2 RB Leipzig - Match Report & Highlights - Sky Sports|publisher=skysports.com|access-date= 26 December 2019}}</ref> helping Lyon to secure their way into the Champions League round of 16. His side later upset both [[Juventus]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] to reach the semi-finals, where they were beaten by [[Bayern Munich]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lyon 0-3 Bayern Munich: Bayern breeze through to final showdown with PSG |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53815521 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=20 August 2020 |language=en |date=19 August 2017}}</ref>

===Roma===
On 11 June 2023, it was announced that Aouar had signed a five-year contract with [[Serie A]] club [[A.S. Roma|Roma]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Houssem Aouar signs for the Giallorossi! |url=https://www.asroma.com/en/news/68777/houssem-aouar-signs-for-the-giallorossi |access-date=2023-07-01 |website=www.asroma.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-06-11 |title=Aouar signs for Roma on free transfer from Lyon |url=https://www.espn.in/football/story/_/id/37836502/houssem-aouar-signs-roma-free-transfer-lyon |access-date=2023-07-01 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> Later that year, on 26 August, he scored his first goal in a 2–1 away defeat against [[Hellas Verona FC|Hellas Verona]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/679234/as-roma-hellas-verona |title=Hellas Verona 2–1 AS Roma |publisher=ESPN |date=26 August 2023 }}</ref>

===Al-Ittihad===
On 16 July 2024, Aouar signed for Saudi club [[Al-Ittihad Club (Jeddah)|Al-Ittihad]] for a reported fee of €12 million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Salem |first1=Omar |title=Official: Ittihad Jeddah announce Houssem Aouar signing |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2024/07/17/ittihad-sign-houssem-aouar/ |access-date=17 July 2024 |work=KingFut |date=17 July 2024}}</ref>

==International career==
===France===
In 2014, Aouar was called up to the [[France national under-17 football team|France under-17 national team]], but only played one game. In 2019, he was a starter throughout [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|the UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] for the [[France national under-21 football team|France under-21 national team]], eventually being eliminated by [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/match/2027439--spain-vs-france/lineups/?iv=true|title=Spain versus France Match Report|publisher=[[UEFA]]|access-date=31 August 2020|date=28 June 2019}}</ref>

In November 2019, Aouar was called up to the [[France national football team|France national team]], but was unable to join the team due to suffering an injury. He was not replaced in the squad.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 November 2020 |title=Bleus: Houssem Aouar, blessé, déclare forfait pour le rassemblement (Deschamps) |url=https://www.beinsports.com/france/equipe-de-france-de-football/news/bleus-houssem-aouar-blesse-declare-forfait-po/1580269 |access-date=9 January 2023 |website=[[beIN Sports]] |language=Fr}}</ref> On 26 August 2020, Aouar received his first call-up for France to prepare for [[2020–21 UEFA Nations League]] matches against [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] and [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in early September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fff.fr/equipes-de-france/1/france-a/derniere-selection|title=Dernière sélection|work=[[French Football Federation]]|date=26 August 2020|access-date=31 August 2020|language=fr}}</ref> However, on 27 August, he tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] during a regular test carried out by Lyon, amid its [[COVID-19 pandemic in France|pandemic in France]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ol.fr/en/contents/articles/2020/08/28/club-statement|title=Club statement|publisher=[[Olympique Lyonnais]]|access-date=28 August 2020|date=31 August 2020}}</ref> he was put into isolation for a fortnight and had to skip training for at least 10 to 15 days. Therefore, France decided to replace him with [[Nabil Fekir]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/ca/soccer/news/lyon-star-aouar-tests-positive-for-covid-19-ahead-of-ligue-1-season-opener/1w4k8vo7lgl4s18jn1ntsevw1j|title=Lyon star Aouar tests positive for Covid-19 ahead of Ligue 1 season opener|publisher=[[Sporting News]]|first=James|last=Westwood|access-date=29 August 2020|date=31 August 2020}}</ref> Aouar eventually made his France debut on 7 October 2020 in a 7–1 [[Friendly (association football)|friendly]] win over [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[ESPN]]|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match?gameId=585176|title=France v Ukraine game report|date=7 October 2020}}</ref>

===Algeria===
[[File:Djamel Belmadi avec Houssem Aouar 2024.jpg|thumb|Aouar and Djamel Belmadi in a press conference before the match against Mauritania at the 2024 Africa Cup of Nations]]
In March 2023, Aouar switched his international allegiance from his birth to the football federation of the country of his parents, Algeria. In an interview with the [[Algerian Football Federation]], he said, "the president held out his hand to me and it seemed like it was just meant to be. I had a second chance and I jumped on it." He also added that he "regretted" having played for France, saying that he felt he "hadn't made the best choice".<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 March 2023 |title=Can Algeria switch help relaunch Aouar's career? |url=https://www.ligue1.com/Articles/Opinion/2023/03/17/can-algeria-switch-help-relaunch-houssem-aouar-career-lyon |access-date=18 March 2023 |website=[[Ligue 1]]}}</ref> On 18 June 2023, he made his debut for [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] against [[Uganda national football team|Uganda]] in the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations qualification|African Cup of Nations qualification]] match.<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 June 2023 |title=First match of Aouar with Algeria|url=https://rmcsport.bfmtv.com/football/serie-a/algerie-les-grands-debuts-d-aouar-avec-les-fennecs-lors-d-un-succes-contre-l-ouganda_AV-202306180373.html}}</ref>

In December 2023, he was named in Algeria's squad for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.algerie-focus.com/can-2024-lalgerie-devoile-sa-liste-officielle-qui-sont-les-fennecs-prets-a-conquerir-lafrique/|title=CAN 2024 : L'Algérie Dévoile sa Liste Officielle – Qui Sont les Fennecs Prêts à Conquérir l'Afrique ?|language=French|date=30 December 2023|access-date=12 January 2024|publisher=Algérie-Focus}}</ref> On 19 December 2025, Aouar withdrew from the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]] due to injury, and was replaced by [[Himad Abdelli]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Blow for Algeria as key midfielder ruled out of Cup of Nations |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/blow-algeria-key-midfielder-ruled-out-cup-nations-2025-12-19/ |publisher=Reuters |access-date=24 December 2025 |date=19 December 2025 |url-status=live}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Aouar is an [[attacking midfielder]] who can play anywhere in midfield, and has been praised for his excellent technical ability and calmness with the ball at his feet.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46390699|title=Houssem Aouar: Meet the Lyon player Pep Guardiola calls 'incredible'|work=BBC Sport |date=29 November 2018}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Aouar holds French and Algerian nationalities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vavel.com/fr/football/lyon/720763-qui-es-tu-houssem-aouar.html|title=Qui es-tu, Houssem Aouar ?|last=Vavel|date=14 November 2016|work=VAVEL.com|access-date=5 February 2018|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/C-est-officiel-houssem-aouar-representera-l-algerie-en-equipe-nationale/1386165 | title=C'est officiel, Houssem Aouar représentera l'Algérie en équipe nationale }}</ref> He holds [[Juninho Pernambucano|Juninho]] and [[Zinedine Zidane]] as role models.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/the-young-lyon-wanted-in-liverpool-and-barcelona-meet-ligue/3o3b1108p64o1iolo7ujoqv2m|title=The Young Lyon wanted in Liverpool and Barcelona - Meet Ligue 1 Rising Star Houssem Aouar {{!}} Goal.com|access-date=30 November 2018|language=en}}</ref> He is a Muslim.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-01-28 |title=Houssem Aouar victime de sa pratique de l'islam |url=https://www.tsa-algerie.com/houssem-aouar-victime-de-sa-pratique-de-lislam/ |access-date=2024-07-30 |website=TSA |language=fr}}</ref>

